          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>
                                        <date>April 13th 5617—1851</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Rev &amp; Dr Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">On the other page I forward<lb/> you some
                                        information—or rather as <del>I</del> we editors<lb/> were
                                        wont to term it—an item—which if<lb/> it meet your
                                        approbation you are at<lb/> liberty to insert in your
                                        valuable periodical.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have been in receipt within the past<lb/> two
                                        weeks of two new Jewish journals one<lb/> a childish affair
                                        published in <placeName>N.Y</placeName> under<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr Isaacs</persName> supervision and the other by<lb/>
                                        <persName>Julius Eckman</persName> of <placeName>San
                                                  Francisco</placeName> called the<lb/> Gleaner a
                                        very indifferent affair in my<lb/> estimation I assure you,
                                        and one which unless<lb/> I much mistake is destined to be
                                        short-<lb/>-lived. The establishment of a sterling
                                        weekly<lb/> journal devoted to the cause of our Faith<lb/>
                                        and the development of the intellectual<lb/> resources of
                                        the Hebrews of the <placeName>U. S</placeName> issued<lb/>
                                        and published at <placeName>N. Y</placeName> or
                                                  <placeName>Phila</placeName> I am<lb/> quite
                                        confident would in due time<lb/> meet with abundant success
                                        and be<lb/> a source of profit and incalculable<lb/> benefit
                                        to both the proprietor and the<lb/> Jews of this Country.
                                        Such a journal<lb/> I looked for in the "Advocate" but
                                        as<lb/> yet it has not made its appearance</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>and respecting its fate I am yet in ignorance. I<lb/> am aware that
                                        the publication of such a journ<lb/>-al as I have named
                                        requires the possession<lb/> of a large capital in order to
                                        fully &amp; widely es-<lb/>-tablish its reputation resorting
                                        to those collater<lb/>-al means now made use of by every new
                                        en-<lb/>-terprise to bring its merits fully before the<lb/>
                                        public, and besides the requisite capital
                                        indi-<lb/>-fatigable labor and the voluntary and
                                        continued<lb/> efforts of the editor &amp; contributors are
                                        necessary<lb/> &amp; indispensable to secure its success.
                                        Notwith-<lb/>-standing all this I believe sanguinely in the
                                        ulti-<lb/>-mate prosperity of the undertaking and hope<lb/>
                                        yet to see it carried out. should I be spared<lb/> to
                                        acquire <del>first</del> independence so far as the<lb/>
                                        pecuniary affairs of this world go—and my<lb/> love of
                                        literature still continue unabated<lb/> (and like the
                                        ancient fount I think it will)<lb/> I sometimes think it may
                                        be reasoned for<lb/> me to take the <sic>iniatry</sic> step
                                        or rather (as<lb/> that has already been done so ably by you
                                        &amp; others)<lb/> to second &amp; carry out those
                                        principles which<lb/> will ultimately place our nation or
                                        people<lb/> in that position the God of Nature &amp;
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName> intended<lb/> they
                                        should hold. Permit me to assure you of my
                                        distin-<lb/>-guished &amp; most sincere regard and believe
                                        me your<lb/> friend most truly   <persName role="author">B
                                                  F. Peixotto</persName></p>
                              <p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>, Editor, etc</p>
                    </body>
